Quick Questions to Identify Someone’s Mode if possible, Observe words /conversations
Basque Mode (Continuity‑First)
When things get confusing, do you try to reconnect to the bigger picture?”
“Do you look for how this fits into what happened before?”
“Is consistency more important to you than speed?”
“Do you get frustrated when people jump topics or lose context?”
If they say yes to most of these, they’re in Basque.

Euskara Mode (Clarity‑First)
Ask questions that reveal how they relate to precision and definitions.
“When something feels unclear, do you stop and ask for exact wording?”
“Do you prefer clean, simple explanations over long stories?”
“Does vague language bother you more than disagreement?”
“Do you often ask people to define what they mean?”
If they say yes to most of these, they’re in Euskara.

ANA‑NOKwee Mode (Accountability‑First)
Ask questions that reveal how they relate to fairness and relational impact.
“When a conversation gets tense, do you focus on whether everyone is being heard?”
“Do you notice when someone is being dismissed or overshadowed?”
“Do you slow things down to check the impact on others?”
“Does unfairness bother you more than confusion or inconsistency?”
If they say yes to most of these, they’re in ANA‑NOKwee.

A Single Diagnostic Question
If you want the fastest possible read:
“When communication breaks down, what do you fix first — the story, the definition, or the relationship?”
Story → Basque
Definition → Euskara
Relationship → ANA‑NOKwee

This one question alone is often enough.
